    {
      "num": 1,
      "text": "Which money laundering stage involves converting illicit funds into seemingly legitimate assets or investments to distance them from their criminal source?",
      "tag": "Money Laundering - Process Stages",
      "options": [
        "C. Integration",
        "D. Structuring",
        "B. Layering",
        "A. Placement"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "Layering is the second stage where criminals conduct complex financial transactions to obscure the audit trail and distance funds from their illegal origin. Per CFE Manual, layering involves moving funds through multiple accounts, jurisdictions, or instruments to create confusion and separate the money from its criminal source.",
      "justification_wrong": "Placement introduces illicit funds into the financial system. Integration reinvests laundered funds into the legitimate economy. Structuring (smurfing) is a placement technique avoiding reporting thresholds. Layering specifically describes the obfuscation process through complex transactions designed to hide the money's origin through multiple transfers and conversions.",
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_001_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 2,
      "text": "In money laundering detection, which red flag most strongly indicates potential structuring or 'smurfing' activities designed to evade currency transaction reporting requirements?",
      "tag": "Money Laundering",
      "options": [
        "D. Discrepancies between reported income and lifestyle expenditures",
        "A. Multiple cash deposits just below $10,000 threshold across different branches",
        "B. Wire transfers to jurisdictions with bank secrecy laws",
        "C. Use of shell companies for transaction layering"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "Structuring involves deliberately breaking large cash amounts into smaller deposits below the $10,000 Currency Transaction Report threshold to avoid reporting requirements under the Bank Secrecy Act. Multiple sub-threshold deposits across locations or time periods constitute the primary red flag for smurfing, representing the placement stage of money laundering.",
      "justification_wrong": "Wire transfers to secrecy havens, shell company usage, and income-lifestyle discrepancies are money laundering indicators but don't specifically evidence structuring. These represent layering, integration, or general financial crime red flags rather than the deliberate transaction-splitting behavior characteristic of structuring schemes under anti-money laundering regulations.",
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_001_en.json"
    },
