    {
      "num": 14,
      "text": "A fraud examiner traces $2.3 million through seven shell companies across four jurisdictions within 72 hours of initial deposit. Transactions involve cryptocurrency conversion, real estate purchases, and luxury goods acquisitions. Under the three-stage money laundering model, which stage is most clearly evident?",
      "tag": "Money Laundering - Layering Stage",
      "options": [
        "A. Layering stage: multiple complex transactions designed to obscure the audit trail and separate illicit funds from their criminal source",
        "B. Placement stage: initial introduction of criminal proceeds into the legitimate financial system",
        "D. Structuring stage: breaking large transactions into smaller amounts to avoid reporting thresholds",
        "C. Integration stage: creating appearance of legitimate wealth and reintroducing funds into the economy"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "Layering involves complex, rapid transactions across multiple entities and jurisdictions to obscure origin, precisely matching the scenario. Per CFE Manual 2024, seven shell companies, cryptocurrency conversion, and cross-border movements within 72 hours exemplify classic layering techniques. The complexity and speed distinguish this from placement (initial entry) or integration (final legitimization of funds).",
      "justification_wrong": "Placement occurs at initial deposit, not subsequent movement. Integration involves final reintroduction appearing legitimate (e.g., business income), not ongoing transfers. Structuring (smurfing) involves threshold avoidance through transaction division, not multi-jurisdictional complexity. The Manual identifies rapid, complex cross-border transfers through multiple entities as definitive layering characteristics designed to defeat audit trails.",
      "difficulty": "HARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_001_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 15,
      "text": "A CFE identifies three wire transfers totaling $2.8 million moved through multiple accounts in different jurisdictions within 48 hours, with no apparent business purpose. This pattern most likely indicates which money laundering stage?",
