    {
      "num": 16,
      "text": "An investigator traces funds through six jurisdictions: wire transfer from Company A (US) → Bank B (Cyprus) → Shell Corp C (BVI) → Trading Account D (Singapore) → Cash withdrawal E (Dubai) → Real estate purchase F (London). Which money laundering stage is represented by the Cyprus to Singapore transfers?",
      "tag": "Money Laundering",
      "options": [
        "A. Placement stage—introducing illicit funds into the financial system",
        "C. Integration stage—creating legitimate appearance for reinvestment",
        "D. Structuring stage—breaking transactions into amounts below reporting thresholds",
        "B. Layering stage—separating funds from illegal source through complex transactions"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "Per CFE Manual 2024, layering involves creating complex transaction chains across multiple jurisdictions to obscure audit trails and ownership. The Cyprus→BVI→Singapore sequence with entity type changes (bank→shell company→trading account) exemplifies classic layering tactics designed to distance funds from origin and complicate investigative tracing efforts.",
      "justification_wrong": "Placement occurs when funds first enter the system (Company A transfer). Integration is the final stage (London real estate purchase providing legitimacy). Structuring involves transaction amount manipulation. The multi-jurisdictional transfers with entity complexity definitively represent layering per CFE three-stage money laundering framework.",
      "difficulty": "HARD",
